{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Mulheres amamentando crian\'e7as menores de 6 meses de idade (WHO: Noting that yellow fever vaccine is a live vaccine, a risk vs benefit assessment should be undertaken for all pregnant and lactating women. In areas where YF is endemic, or during outbreaks, the benefits of YF vaccination are likely to far outweigh the risk of potential transmission of vaccine virus to the fetus or infant. Pregnant women and nursing mothers should be counselled on the potential benefits and risks of vaccination so that they may make an informed decision about vaccination. Lactating women should be advised that the benefits of breastfeeding far outweigh alternatives. Vaccination is recommended, if indicated, for pregnant or breastfeeding women travelling to endemic areas when such travel cannot be avoided or postponed.);\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Pessoas com hipersensibilidade* ou alergia grave ao ovo (CDC: *Although hypersensitivity is a contraindication, yellow fever vaccination can be considered in the setting of appropriate desensitization.). CDC: Yellow fever vaccine is contraindicated for people with a history of acute hypersensitivity reaction to a previous dose of the vaccine, as well as those who have a history of reaction to any component of the vaccine, including eggs, egg products, chicken proteins, or gelatin. The stopper of the vaccine vial contains dry natural latex rubber that might also cause an allergic reaction. However, allergic reactions to latex after vaccinations, including anaphylaxis, are rare for patients. People who can eat eggs or egg products may receive the vaccine. For egg- sensitive individuals, including those with a history of minor reactions, a scratch test or intradermal test can be performed prior to administering the vaccine to check for reactivity. If a person has a history of severe egg sensitivity or has a positive skin test to the vaccine, and vaccination is recommended because of his or her destination-specific risk, desensitization can be performed under direct supervision of a physician. The physician should be experienced in desensitization and the management of anaphylaxis. The desensitization procedure is detailed in the product insert.\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}Pessoas que vivem com HIV e que tem contagem de c\'e9lulas CD4 menor que 350 (CDC: Symptomatic HIV infection or CD4+ value <200/mm3[cubic] (or <15% of total lymphocytes in children younger than 6 years)). Asymptomatic HIV Infection: 1. Asymptomatic HIV infection is a precaution for yellow fever vaccination when CD4+ T-lymphocyte values are 200\f2\endash 499/mm3 or 15%\endash 24% of total lymphocytes in children younger than age 6 years. If these patients cannot avoid travel to a yellow fever-endemic area, vaccination can be considered after discussing the potential risks and benefits with the patient. If vaccinated, they should be monitored closely for adverse events. Although large prospective, randomized trials have not been performed to adequately address the safety and efficacy of yellow fever vaccine among this group of moderately immune-suppressed patients, limited studies have reported no serious adverse events.\f0  \f2 HIV-infection has been associated with a reduced immunologic response to yellow fever vaccine. Because vaccination of asymptomatic HIV-infected people might be less effective than that for people not infected with HIV, measurement of their neutralizing antibody response to vaccination should be considered before travel. Contact the appropriate state health department or the Division of Vector-borne Diseases at CDC by phoning 970-221-6400 to discuss the need for serologic testing\f0 ;\par
{\pntext\f4\'B7\tab}CDC: Thymus disorder with abnormal immune cell function. Yellow fever vaccine is contraindicated for people with thymus disorders that are associated with abnormal immune cell function, such as thymomas or myasthenia gravis. This contraindication includes people who have a history of thymectomy for thymoma or other thymus disorders. These patients are advised to avoid travel to yellow fever-endemic areas. If travel to these areas is unavoidable, patients should be advised of the risks associated with non- vaccination, instructed in the methods for avoiding mosquitoes, and issued a medical waiver to meet entry requirements. To date, there is no evidence of immune dysfunction or increased risk of yellow fever vaccine-associated serious adverse events in people who have undergone incidental surgical removal of their thymus or have had radiation therapy in the distant past. These patients may receive yellow fever vaccine, if indicated, based on their destination-specific yellow fever risk. (look for a list of conditions associated with each of the contraindicated items, to make the questions more specific) Thymoma is considered to be a thymus disorder potentially associated with abnormal immune cell function, even after the thymoma has been removed surgically. As such, a history of thymoma is a contraindication to yellow fever vaccination. The traveler should not receive the vaccination and should be advised to avoid traveling to Trinidad or other yellow fever-endemic countries. If travel is unavoidable, advise of the risks of non-vaccination, instruct in methods for avoiding mosquitoes, and issue a medical waiver to meet entry requirements;\par
